com.github.thorbenkuck.netcom2.network.client

Interface RemoteObjectFactory


  • public interface RemoteObjectFactory
    Implementations will create RemoteObjects.

    Those RemoteObjects are proxies. There should be NO reason to check for that.

    • Method Detail

      • setDefaultFallback

        void setDefaultFallback(Runnable runnable)
        Sets the default Runnable fallback, if the requested Class is not registered.

        This allows you, to say what to do, if the RemoteObject is not registered.

        The Runnable will be executed, if and only if the requested Object is not registered i.e. if a RemoteObjectNotRegisteredException is thrown on the Server. Else, the received Exception will be rethrown, encapsulated in a RemoteRequestException.

        Parameters:
        runnable - the runnable, that should be executed, if the requested Class is not present.

      • setFallback

        void setFallback(Class<?> clazz,
                 Runnable runnable)
        Adds a fallback, mapped to a certain Class.

        If a RemoteObject of the type clazz is not registered, this runnable will be executed.

        If the provided Class is requested, this fallback runnable is used preferred over setDefaultFallback(Runnable). Otherwise, the behaviour is the same.

        Parameters:
        runnable - the runnable, that should be executed, if the requested class is not present
        clazz - the class, that was requested

      • setFallbackInstance

        <T,S extends T> void setFallbackInstance(Class<T> clazz,
                                         S instance)
        Adds a fallback instance, that should be executed if the remote-object is not registered.

        If the provided Class is requested, this fallback runnable is used preferred over setFallback(Class, Runnable). Otherwise, the behaviour is the same.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the Type of the requested remote object
        S - the Type of the fallback instance
        Parameters:
        clazz - the class, that was requested
        instance - the instance, that should be used if the remote object is not registered.

      • create

        <T> T create(Class<T> type,
             Runnable customFallback)
        Creates the RemoteObject.

        Calling this method will ignore previously set instances of fallbacks.

        So, if any callbacks are set, this method will ignore them and set the provided runnable to be used, if the Object is not registered at the Server-side

        Type Parameters:
        T - the Type of the requested RemoteObject
        Parameters:
        type - the Class of the requested RemoteObject
        Returns:

      • create

        <T> T create(Class<T> type,
             T fallbackInstance)
        Creates the RemoteObject.

        Calling this method will ignore previously set instances of fallbacks.

        So, if any callbacks are set, this method will ignore them and set the provided instance to be used, if the Object is not registered at the Server-side. Then, it will execute the requested Method on the provided fallbackInstance.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the Type of the requested RemoteObject
        Parameters:
        type - the Class of the requested RemoteObject
        fallbackInstance - the instance that should be used, if the requested Object is not registered
        Returns:
        an proxy instance for the requested type
        See Also:
        setDefaultFallback(Runnable), setFallback(Class, Runnable), setFallbackInstance(Class, Object)

      • createWithoutFallback

        <T> T createWithoutFallback(Class<T> type)
        This method will produce an Proxy for the RemoteObject.

        In contrast to the other create Methods, this will result in an Proxy with no fallback.

        This means, if the requested Object is not registered at the Server-side, calling any method of the Proxy will result in an RemoteObjectNotRegisteredException.

        If you plan on using the RemoteObjects in any Module, that does not know of the Network, this is not recommended.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the Type of the requested RemoteObject
        Parameters:
        type - the Class of the requested RemoteObject
        Returns:
        an new Proxy class of the provided type.
